Grants – Tranche Governance Module

Financial authority mutation layer for grant disbursement tranches.

This module does not “edit payments.”

It records irreversible financial intent while preserving immutable authority history.

If this module deletes, overwrites, or mutates authority casually, your financial audit trail collapses.

Core Principle

History is immutable.
Authority is superseded, never erased.
Financial correction is additive, not destructive.

Reversal is not deletion.

Compensation is not overwrite.

Everything is explicit.

Domain Responsibilities

This module owns:

Tranche reversal (authoritative supersession)

Tranche compensation (financial counter-entry)

Immutable decision recording

Explicit execution mutation (status change)

Tranche event audit stream

It does not:

Execute fund transfers

Modify case lifecycle directly

Bypass DecisionService

Delete tranche records

Retroactively rewrite history

Financial Model

A tranche represents a planned or released portion of a grant.

Status values include:

RELEASED

REVERSED

(others not shown here)

Financial integrity requires:

Released tranches may be reversed

Reversed tranches may be compensated

History must remain replayable

Authority Architecture

All authoritative actions pass through:

DecisionService.applyDecision(...)

TrancheService never writes authority directly.

Why?

Because authority must:

Be immutable

Be supersedable

Be ledger-bound

Be replayable

DecisionService is the constitutional boundary.

Reversing a Tranche

reverseTranche()

Preconditions:

Tranche exists

Status is RELEASED

An authoritative DecisionType.TRANCHE exists

Prior decision is not superseded

Flow:

Locate prior authoritative decision

Apply new decision that supersedes prior

Explicitly mutate tranche status → REVERSED

Record tranche event

The previous authority is not deleted.

It is superseded.

That distinction protects audit integrity.

Why Supersede Instead of Delete?

Deleting authority:

Breaks replay determinism

Breaks audit continuity

Breaks explainability

Creates silent financial gaps

Superseding authority:

Preserves history

Marks evolution of intent

Enables deterministic reconstruction

Financial systems must evolve forward, not backward.

Compensating a Reversed Tranche

compensateReversedTranche()

Compensation does not modify the reversed tranche.

It creates a new tranche:

plannedAmount.neg()

plannedPercent.neg()

sequence offset (+1000)

status RELEASED

Negative value is intentional.

This encodes financial correction structurally.

Not narratively.

Why Create a New Tranche Instead of Editing?

Because financial correctness requires:

Additive correction

Clear compensating entry

Balance-preserving modeling

Deterministic ledger replay

Editing a reversed tranche would:

Destroy original financial intent

Obscure compensation semantics

Corrupt explainability

This design mirrors accounting systems:

Credits and debits.
Not edits and deletes.

Transaction Guarantees

All operations wrapped in:

prisma.$transaction(...)

Guarantees:

Authority mutation

Status mutation

Tranche event creation

are atomic.

If DecisionService fails → tranche status not mutated.

If tranche update fails → authority not applied.

No partial financial mutation.

Execution Effect

Effect used:

effect: { kind: "EXECUTION_VERIFIED" }

This is currently static.

Future evolution:

Expand DecisionEffect union.

Do not duplicate tranche logic.

Authority semantics belong in DecisionEffect domain.

Invariants

Only RELEASED tranche may be reversed.

Only REVERSED tranche may be compensated.

Reversal must supersede prior authoritative decision.

Compensation must create negative-value tranche.

No deletion of tranche records.

No bypassing DecisionService.

All operations transactional.

Break these and financial drift becomes invisible.

Audit Trail Layers

This module produces three audit layers:

Decision record (authority layer)

Tranche status mutation (projection layer)

TrancheEvent (domain event stream)

All three together produce explainable financial causality.

Remove one and clarity degrades.

Concurrency Considerations

Potential race condition:

Two reversal attempts simultaneously.

Mitigation required:

Add unique partial constraint on (trancheId, status=REVERSED)

Or use SELECT FOR UPDATE on tranche row

Or check status inside transaction

Financial mutation must not double-execute.

Scalability Characteristics

Current behavior:

Single-row tranche lookup

Single decision supersession

Single compensating tranche insert

O(1) transaction complexity

Future scaling options:

Index decision.intentContext JSON path

Partition trancheEvent by grantId

Add deterministic compensating sequence scheme

Design remains horizontally safe.

Observability Expectations

Each reversal must record:

Actor identity

Superseded decision ID

Reason

Timestamp

Each compensation must record:

Compensating tranche ID

Reversed tranche ID

Financial delta

Reason

Financial systems must be reconstructible from immutable facts.

Mental Model

Think of this module as a financial correction engine.

A released tranche is an executed financial intent.

If that intent is wrong:

You do not erase it.
You record a superseding authority.
You explicitly reverse its status.
You create a compensating financial entry.

History remains intact.
Correction is explicit.
Ledger remains replayable.

If auditors replay this system five years from now,
they must see:

Original release
→ Reversal authority
→ Compensating tranche

Nothing missing.
Nothing overwritten.
Nothing ambiguous.

That is the standard.

Ready for the next domain boundary.
